    "summary": "Creative, organized, analytic, an agent of change, peer review innovation expert, an advocate of inclusion and diversity, self-steamed, and self-drive. \nVice President of European Association for Science Editors (EASE)\nChair of Peer Review Workbench\nCo-chair of NISO's EDIA committee\nCo-chair of the 2019 peer review week organization committee; co-chair of the Event and International Outreach Committee of 2020 peer review week; member of PEERE: New Frontiers of peer review; member of peer review taxonomy working group at STM/NISO; \n\nBahar is Peer Review Innovation Lead in the Innovation Center of Expertise at STM Journals, Elsevier. She works on several initiatives related to the peer review process, all of which are designed to improve the quality and fairness of peer review, recognize reviewers' contributions to the progress of science while improving trust in science. She started her career at Elsevier as a managing editor for physics titles. Bahar received her Ph.D. in Theoretical Physics from the University of Amsterdam (UvA) in 2010 and was a postdoc researcher at the Max Planck Institute for the Science of Light (MPL) before joining Elsevier in 2012.\nBahar's recent publications included the impact of COVID-19 lockdown on women academics, gender bias in peer review at large scale, peer review quality perceptions, and the impact of a pilot experiment she ran on open peer review on reviewer behavior. \n\nSpecialties: product ownership, product management, peer review innovations, scholarly publishing, physics",
