        {
            "url": "https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0257919",
            "title": "Gender gap in journal submissions and peer review during the first wave of the COVID-19 pandemic. A study on 2329 Elsevier journals",
            "description": "During the early months of the COVID-19 pandemic, there was an unusually high submission rate of scholarly articles. Given that most academics were forced to work from home. We looked into over 5 million authors' and referees' performances between 2018 and 2020 and found out that during the first wave of the pandemic, women submitted proportionally fewer manuscripts than men. This deficit was especially pronounced among more junior cohorts of women academics.",
            "image": "https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/sync/C4D27AQG1G_6TqzM2DQ/articleshare-shrink_800/0/1694781181166?e=1696442400&v=beta&t=xU0Gz9oBTO7BCan8XCcF3MvHCSVqIjAPsjwA4u99uZs"
        },
        {
            "url": null,
            "title": "Peer review and gender bias: A study on 145 scholarly journals",
            "description": "We examined gender bias in peer review with data for 145 journals in various fields of research, including about 1.7 million authors and 740,000 referees. We reconstructed three possible sources of bias, i.e., the editorial selection of referees, referee recommendations, and editorial decisions, and examined all their possible relationships. Results showed that manuscripts written by women as solo authors or coauthored by women were treated even more favorably by referees and editors.",
            "image": null
